Introduction and background

This is one of the two Capstone-Project-Case-Studies for the Google Data Analytics Certificate Program which aims to solve real world types of business problems using data analytics. This markdown document follows and applies the Ask-Prepare-Process-Analyze-Share-Act framework as a methodical approach to addressing the key areas of consideration within the data analysis process.

About the company

Urka Sren and Sando Mur founded Bellabeat, a high-tech company that manufactures health-focused smart products. Sren used her background as an artist to develop beautifully designed technology that informs and inspires women around the world. Collecting data on activity, sleep, stress, and reproductive health has allowed Bellabeat to empower women with knowledge about their own health and habits. Since it was founded in 2013, Bellabeat has grown rapidly and quickly positioned itself as a tech-driven wellness company for women.

By 2016, Bellabeat had opened offices around the world and launched multiple products. Bellabeat products became available through a growing number of online retailers in addition to their own e-commerce channel on their website. The company has invested in traditional advertising media, such as radio, out-of-home billboards, print, and television, but focuses on digital marketing extensively. Bellabeat invests year-round in Google Search, maintaining active Facebook and Instagram pages, and consistently engages consumers on Twitter. Additionally, Bellabeat runs video ads on Youtube and display ads on the Google Display Network to support campaigns around key marketing dates.

Business question

Sren knows that an analysis of Bellabeats available consumer data would reveal more opportunities for growth. She has asked the marketing analytics team to focus on a Bellabeat product and analyze smart device usage data in order to gain insight into how people are already using their smart devices. Then, using this information, she would like high-level recommendations for how these trends can inform Bellabeat marketing strategy

Analysis and Visualizations of our data

Plotting a few explorations to confirm some trends and correllations

The visualizations below, gives us a clear indication that more physical movements lead to more calories being burnt, and better sleep. A user whose goal is to burn more calories on a daily basis and enjoy all the benefits of healthy sleep will want to increase how active they are

ggplot(daily_activity, aes(TrackerDistance, Calories, size = Calories, color = Calories)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.4)+ guides(size = "none")+ geom_smooth(method = loess) + labs(title = "Plotting the tracker distance vs the amount of calories burnt", subtitle = "We see that as expected, the longer the distance, the more calories were burnt")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

The correlation between our active users and the medically recommended amount of sleep the recommended sleep average for an adult is between 7 to 9 hours. its is highly recommended to get this complete amount every day as only 23% maximum amount is spent in deep sleep which is not only specially important for general wellness, but as well as when the body renews itself.

ggplot(sleep_day1, aes(x = TotalMinutesAsleep, fill = "orangered3")) + geom_histogram(bins = 10)+
geom_vline(xintercept = 420, linetype = "solid", color = "lightskyblue4")+
  geom_vline(xintercept = 540, linetype = "solid", color = "lightskyblue4")+
  labs(title = "Recommnended sleep average, compared to recorded average of fitbit users",
       subtitle= "The maximum number of most fitbit users fall in line with the recommended value, 420 to 540 minutes")+ guides(fill = "none")

We see that even if many users sleep the required amount, a large amount of users still sleep a little less than that amount.

Lets create buckets with our total intensity data, mutate to low, medium, high and very high intensities and categorize by day of the week

hourly_intensities1$Category <- case_when(
hourly_intensities1$TotalIntensity <= 6 ~ "low_intensity",
hourly_intensities1$TotalIntensity <= 13 ~ "Medium_intensity",
hourly_intensities1$TotalIntensity <= 25 ~ "High_intensity",
hourly_intensities1$TotalIntensity <= 180 ~ "Very_high_intensity"
)
colnames(hourly_intensities1)
## [1] "Id"               "ActivityHour"     "TotalIntensity"   "AverageIntensity"
## [5] "wday"             "Category"

Plot the various categories of intensities and group by day of the week

ggplot(hourly_intensities1) + geom_col(aes(Category, TotalIntensity, fill = Category))+ facet_grid(~wday)+ guides(fill = "none")+ scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2") + labs(title = "Average intensities by day of the week",subtitle = "We notice that Sundays represent the most intense activity day on average")+ theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

Act

This analysis of the fitness tracking smart device data as published and retrieved from Kaggle uncovered some insights on the current ways as well as future benefits that Bellabeat Wellness Technology could explore. We started by taking a glimpse of our data to confirm that more calories were burnt depending on how far our user was willing to travel. Next we took a glimpse of the sleep data recorded and confirmed that most count of our users were able to sleep for the required national amount. Next we checked the sedentary time spent and the Total minutes asleep, here we noticed an inverse relationship, the total active minutes and tracker distance however showed a more positive ~ 1 correlation. This shows the future fitbit users the benefit of using the devices and subscriptions. To check what day of the week the users tend to go much harder than on other days, we categorized the intensities after finding the summary of the recorded data, the correlation showed that the users had more intensity on Sundays and least on fridays.

Recommendations

On days when the app records high intensity work outs, a reminder can be sent to encourage 7 to 9 hours recommended sleep. On fridays we record the lowest amount of intensities, a reminder can be sent on this day every week to encourage users. Users are to be encouraged to submit their weight log data such as BMI for better customer engagement and service, they should be reminded that all individuals that have allowed access to their data are protected by privacy protections. We also notice that regardless of intensity, every active minute or distance spent in any form of workout activity provided benefits to the user in terms of calories burned. Bellabeat can prompt users automatically about projected calories to be burnt per 15 minutes workout activity to encourage users. possibly early in the mornings or late evenings. Lastly, the sleep data and amount of calories burned can act as a campaign topic to attract more users.

Problems with the data

The data set was uploaded 5 years ago, hence its not as current to be relevant for our analysis. The data authenticity can not be totally vouched for as its from a third party on <kaggle.com> the sample size was also much smaller than standard and many values were missing.
